My visual data story

Introduction

In this data story, I analyze and collected the daily commute patterns of students including me and my mates going and returning from UoA. This observational data was collected over multiple days, focusing on commute duration, activities, and time of day.

Main Activities during commute

plot1

The key activities that commuters engaged in throughout their commute are distributed as shown in the bar plot. The most popular activity was texting and calling, which was closely followed by conversing and staring out the window. Sleeping, doing nothing, and using social media were comparatively less common behaviours. This pattern implies that commuters are mostly interacting digitally or observing passively, which may suggest that most commutes offer chances for leisure or distraction rather than active participation in other activities. Another reason why commuters may text/call more compared to other activities could be due to boredom and they may find it rather amusing to talk to people whereas staring out the window could be for people who are less reserved and would rather admire the scenery from the window.

Commute Duration by Transport mode

plot2

The boxplot illustrates how commuting times vary depending on the mode of transport. According to the data, commuters who take the train have the longest commutes, with a wide variety of times recorded. On the other hand, commutes by bus and car (passenger) show rather reasonable and consistent lengths. Walking and bicycling had the shortest commutes, suggesting that active transportation and close proximity lead to faster travel times. The variation in car (driver) durations points to possible variations in traffic or routes that impact commute duration.

Commute Duration Trends Over Time

plot3

The average commute time by hour of the day is displayed in the line plot. Notable variations may be seen in the pattern, with notable peaks appearing in the morning and late afternoon during regular rush hours. This pattern implies that peak traffic times have a significant impact on commute times, which may have an impact on stress levels and activity preferences. The midday decreases that have been noticed could be a sign of less traffic or fewer commutes taking place during off-peak hours.

Conclusion

The graphic data tale offers a thorough summary of the everyday commute habits of college students. According to the data, commuters favour low-effort, distraction-oriented habits, as seen by the fact that they mostly text and stare out the window. The boxplot study also shows that, in accordance with closeness to the campus, bike and pedestrian commutes give the lowest durations, whereas train travels often offer the longest. The line plot further supports the idea that traffic affects travel times by showing distinct peaks in commute duration during regular rush hours. These results highlight how crucial it is to take into account both the time of day and the method of transport when assessing commute experiences and making plans for more effective travel tactics.
